  "articles": [
    {
      "id": "endo_retreatment_step_by_step",
      "title": "Step-by-Step Guide to Endodontic Retreatment",
      "slug": "endodontic-retreatment-step-by-step",
      "summary": "A practical chairside guide to planning and performing endodontic retreatment, from case selection to obturation.",
      "body": "Endodontic retreatment requires a structured approach that begins with careful diagnosis and case selection. Pre-operative radiographs, CBCT when indicated, and a thorough understanding of the existing anatomy and previous treatment are essential.\n\n**1. Access and Removal of Existing Materials**  \nBegin by improving access and identifying all canals. Use magnification and illumination whenever possible. Remove existing coronal restorations or posts as needed, taking care to preserve tooth structure. Gutta-percha removal can be achieved with rotary or reciprocating NiTi files and dedicated solvents in complex cases.\n\n**2. Irrigation and Disinfection Strategy**  \nOnce previous filling materials are removed, focus on re-establishing patency and working length. Copious irrigation with sodium hypochlorite is critical. Activate irrigants mechanically or ultrasonically where possible to disrupt biofilm and improve penetration in isthmuses and lateral anatomy.\n\n**3. Shaping and Glide Path Management**  \nUse controlled, flexible NiTi rotary files to reshape the canal, respecting original anatomy. In retreatment, avoid excessive enlargement that may weaken the root. Glide path verification and frequent recapitulation reduce the risk of ledging and transportation.\n\n**4. Obturation and Sealer Selection**  \nAfter thorough disinfection and a dry canal, select an obturation technique that fits the anatomy and your experience. Bioceramic sealers are advantageous in retreatment cases due to their bioactivity and dimensional stability. Confirm the master cone fit radiographically and proceed with warm or single-cone techniques as indicated.\n\n**5. Restoration and Follow-Up**  \nA well-sealed coronal restoration is as important as the retreatment itself. Plan definitive restoration early and schedule follow-up radiographs to assess healing.\n\nThe following products are commonly used in clinical retreatment protocols and can help standardize your workflow.",
      "tags": [
        "retreatment",
        "endodontics",
        "irrigation",
        "obturation",
        "clinical_guide"
      ],
      "topic": "retreatment",
